          "body": "Verses 6-13 contain some of the most blistering sarcasm in the Pauline corpus. The Corinthians have telescoped the eschaton into the present — they are *already* filled, *already* rich, *already* reigning (4:8, triple *ede*). Paul drives a wedge: 'I wish that you had become kings so that we also might reign with you.' If your reign were real, ours would have arrived too — but look at us. The apostolic catalogue follows (vv. 9-13): condemned to death, a cosmic spectacle, fools, weak, dishonored, hungry, thirsty, poorly clothed, struck, homeless, working with their hands, reviled, persecuted, slandered, reckoned as *perikatharmata* and *peripsema* — the scum scraped off and the filth wiped away. These are the two lowest words in koine Greek for human refuse. Paul's argument is theological: if cruciform suffering is the present shape of the apostolic life — and the apostles are God's exhibit (*apedeixen*, 4:9) — then the Corinthian self-perception is a category error. They have read the wrong chapter of the calendar."
